];

const keyTakeaways = [
  '6-phase implementation process from planning to optimization',
  '30% cost reduction and 24/7 availability outcomes',
  'Platform comparisons and ROI calculation framework',
];

const faqItems = [
  {
    question: 'How much does it cost to implement an enterprise AI chatbot?',
    answer: 'Enterprise AI chatbot implementation costs vary widely: SaaS platforms like Intercom or Drift range from $500–$5,000/month. Custom-built solutions on platforms like IBM Watson or Microsoft Bot Framework cost $50,000–$500,000+ for initial development. Ongoing costs include API fees, maintenance, and staff training. A mid-market deployment typically runs $10,000–$100,000 all-in for year one, with ROI typically achieved within 12–18 months through support cost savings.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How long does enterprise AI chatbot implementation take?',
    answer: 'A basic enterprise chatbot deployment takes 4–8 weeks. A mid-complexity deployment with CRM/helpdesk integrations takes 2–4 months. A fully custom enterprise solution with complex workflows, multiple languages, and deep system integrations takes 6–12 months. The majority of time is spent on data preparation, integration testing, and change management — not the AI training itself.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the typical ROI of an enterprise AI chatbot?',
    answer: 'The average enterprise chatbot delivers 25–40% reduction in support ticket volume within 6 months. Common benchmarks: $2–$8 saved per automated interaction (vs. $10–$25 for live agent), 60–80% first-contact resolution rate, and 30–50% reduction in average handling time for escalated tickets. Most enterprises report full ROI within 12–18 months. High-volume deployments (10,000+ monthly interactions) often see ROI within 6 months.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Which AI chatbot platforms are best for enterprise?',
    answer: 'Top enterprise platforms include: Microsoft Copilot Studio (best for Microsoft 365 environments), IBM Watson Assistant (best for regulated industries), Salesforce Einstein (best for CRM-heavy deployments), ServiceNow Virtual Agent (best for IT service management), and Google Dialogflow CX (best for complex conversation flows). For smaller enterprises, Intercom, Zendesk AI, or Freshdesk offer strong out-of-the-box solutions with lower implementation overhead.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do you integrate an AI chatbot with Salesforce or HubSpot?',
    answer: 'Most enterprise chatbot platforms offer native Salesforce and HubSpot connectors. The integration process involves: (1) authenticating the chatbot platform with your CRM via OAuth or API key, (2) mapping chatbot data fields to CRM fields, (3) configuring triggers for creating/updating records, and (4) testing with sandbox data. Native integrations typically take 1–2 weeks to configure. Custom API integrations require developer resources and take 4–8 weeks.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What compliance standards do enterprise AI chatbots need to meet?',
    answer: 'Required compliance varies by industry: Healthcare requires HIPAA compliance (data encryption, audit trails, BAA with vendor). Finance requires SOC 2 Type II, PCI-DSS for payment data. EU businesses need GDPR compliance (data residency, right to deletion, DPA with vendor). Government agencies often need FedRAMP authorization. Always request compliance documentation from your vendor and ensure your data processing agreements are in place before deployment.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Do AI chatbots replace human customer service agents?',
    answer: 'No — enterprise AI chatbots augment rather than replace human agents in most deployments. The optimal model is AI handling 50–70% of routine, repetitive inquiries (FAQs, order status, password resets) while human agents focus on complex, high-value, and emotionally sensitive interactions. This hybrid model reduces headcount growth rather than eliminating existing roles. Gartner predicts AI will handle 80% of routine customer interactions by 2028 while human agent roles evolve toward advisory and exception management.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How do you measure enterprise chatbot success?',
    answer: 'Key metrics to track: Containment Rate (% of conversations resolved without human escalation — target 60–80%), Customer Satisfaction Score (CSAT — target 4.0+/5.0), First Response Time (should be near-instant vs. minutes for human), Cost Per Conversation (target $0.50–$3.00 vs. $10–$25 human), and Deflection Volume (total tickets avoided). Track these weekly for the first 90 days, monthly thereafter.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What are the biggest risks of enterprise AI chatbot deployment?',
    answer: 'The top risks are: (1) Poor training data leading to incorrect or unhelpful responses — mitigate by starting with a focused scope. (2) Failure to escalate to humans appropriately — always build clear escalation paths. (3) Data privacy violations — ensure end-to-end encryption and compliance. (4) User resistance — invest in change management and internal champions. (5) Scope creep delaying launch — deploy an MVP in 60 days and iterate. Most failed deployments stem from over-ambition, not technical limitations.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What is the difference between a rule-based chatbot and an AI chatbot?',
    answer: 'Rule-based chatbots follow decision trees with fixed responses to predetermined inputs — fast to build but rigid, unable to handle unexpected questions. AI chatbots use natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning to understand intent and generate contextual responses — more flexible, handle varied phrasing, and improve over time. Modern enterprise deployments typically use hybrid systems: AI for understanding intent, rules/workflows for ensuring compliance and predictability in business-critical flows.',
  },
];
